from the pituitary.

01:02:32.430 --> 01:02:34.300
Remember, it doesn't
directly release.

01:02:34.300 --> 01:02:37.950
It's a modulator, a CRH action,
if-then clause, et cetera.

01:02:37.950 --> 01:02:40.950
But those are the two ways
we've heard about oxytocin.

01:02:40.950 --> 01:02:45.690
Oxytocin also works in the
brain as a neurotransmitter

01:02:45.690 --> 01:02:47.550
and neuromodulator.

01:02:47.550 --> 01:02:49.140
And what does it do there?

01:02:49.140 --> 01:02:52.080
It appears to play
a very central role

01:02:52.080 --> 01:02:55.680
in forming attachments,
a very central role

01:02:55.680 --> 01:02:57.780
in forming of pair bonds.

01:02:57.780 --> 01:03:01.040
And it, along with dopamine
and the D2 receptors,

01:03:01.040 --> 01:03:05.110
are critical for female
voles of monogamous species

01:03:05.110 --> 01:03:06.610
to form pair bonds.

01:03:06.610 --> 01:03:11.400
Female humans, when having
sex, secrete lots of oxytocin

01:03:11.400 --> 01:03:14.250
and activate oxytocin
pathways in the brain.

01:03:14.250 --> 01:03:19.040
And it appears to play a role
in the formation of attachment.

01:03:19.040 --> 01:03:22.950
Interestingly-- how's this--
a whole body of research

01:03:22.950 --> 01:03:26.750
now showing that if
you introduce oxytocin

01:03:26.750 --> 01:03:29.770
into the brains of
humans experimentally,

01:03:29.770 --> 01:03:32.900
they become more trusting.

01:03:32.900 --> 01:03:37.800
Amazing body of research where
you take aerosolized oxytocin

01:03:37.800 --> 01:03:40.180
and you spritz it
up people's noses.

01:03:40.180 --> 01:03:41.760
And what they showed
in the studies

01:03:41.760 --> 01:03:44.410
were, number one,
one type of study.

01:03:44.410 --> 01:03:48.360
You then play a clip of
somebody making an argument

01:03:48.360 --> 01:03:51.170
for some stance in
some debate, and people

01:03:51.170 --> 01:03:52.700
believe the person more.

01:03:52.700 --> 01:03:54.900
They find their argument
more convincing.

01:03:54.900 --> 01:03:56.770
They trust the person more.

01:03:56.770 --> 01:03:58.690
Or the other version
that's been shown

01:03:58.690 --> 01:04:01.800
is you spritz oxytocin
up the noses of people,

01:04:01.800 --> 01:04:04.820
and you make them more
cooperative in their game

01:04:04.820 --> 01:04:07.290
theory play, the
ways in which they

01:04:07.290 --> 01:04:10.450
go about playing prisoner's
dilemma and other games

01:04:10.450 --> 01:04:12.780
we will hear about
later on as well.

01:04:12.780 --> 01:04:16.770
This has given rise to a whole
new field-- I kid you not--

01:04:16.770 --> 01:04:19.450
called neuromarketing.

01:04:19.450 --> 01:04:22.880
The notion that if only you
could spritz oxytocin up

01:04:22.880 --> 01:04:26.730
the noses of people right before
your television ad comes on,

01:04:26.730 --> 01:04:29.150
they're going to believe
you when you say it

01:04:29.150 --> 01:04:31.800
will make you happy
to buy our thing.

01:04:31.800 --> 01:04:33.370
And they will fall for it.

01:04:33.370 --> 01:04:35.820
There are actually
neuroendocrinologists

01:04:35.820 --> 01:04:40.050
making a living now selling
their wares to neuromarketing

01:04:40.050 --> 01:04:42.950
people-- self-proclaimed ones.

01:04:42.950 --> 01:04:45.030
No doubt they are
spritzing oxytocin up

01:04:45.030 --> 01:04:48.270
the noses of those
capitalists to get

01:04:48.270 --> 01:04:49.840
them to hire them to do this.

01:04:49.840 --> 01:04:53.660
But oxytocin playing
a role in this.

01:04:53.660 --> 01:04:55.850
So that's kind of interesting.

01:04:55.850 --> 01:04:58.970
Because what's oxytocin
mostly doing in the body?

01:04:58.970 --> 01:05:01.820
The vast majority
of oxytocin is not

01:05:01.820 --> 01:05:04.130
this stuff up in the
brain in these pathways,

01:05:04.130 --> 01:05:07.690
some of them impinging on
dopamine-releasing neurons.

01:05:07.690 --> 01:05:11.000
The vast majority is not
the oxytocin sitting there

01:05:11.000 --> 01:05:13.960
in the hypothalamus doing
something or other to ACTH

01:05:13.960 --> 01:05:15.100
in the pituitary.

01:05:15.100 --> 01:05:18.280
The vast majority is this stuff
coming out of the posterior

01:05:18.280 --> 01:05:19.460
pituitary.

01:05:19.460 --> 01:05:22.670
And what does oxytocin
have to do there?

01:05:22.670 --> 01:05:25.060
It has to do with milk letdown.

01:05:25.060 --> 01:05:27.120
It has to do with nursing.

01:05:27.120 --> 01:05:30.200
And suddenly, instead,
it's playing a role

01:05:30.200 --> 01:05:32.640
in forming sexual pair bonding.

01:05:32.640 --> 01:05:35.800
And the argument is
made that attachment,

01:05:35.800 --> 01:05:40.470
monogamous attachment, sexual
attachment, is in some way,

01:05:40.470 --> 01:05:44.020
evolutionarily a descendent
of the neurobiology

01:05:44.020 --> 01:05:46.660
of mother-offspring attachment.

01:05:46.660 --> 01:05:49.990
That that's where it is
originally being driven by.

01:05:49.990 --> 01:05:53.620
So oxytocin playing
a role there as well.

01:05:53.620 --> 01:05:56.580
Meanwhile, over at the
male end of things,

01:05:56.580 --> 01:05:58.990
up go testosterone
levels during sex.

01:05:58.990 --> 01:06:02.560
In a surprisingly linear
way, the more sexual behavior

01:06:02.560 --> 01:06:04.640
in a male, the higher
testosterone levels

01:06:04.640 --> 01:06:06.100
are found afterward.

01:06:06.100 --> 01:06:09.280
Critically, critically--
stay tuned for a little

01:06:09.280 --> 01:06:13.890
while-- these are elevations
of testosterone in response

01:06:13.890 --> 01:06:15.510
to sexual behavior.

01:06:15.510 --> 01:06:19.570
As we'll see, the evidence
that high testosterone levels

01:06:19.570 --> 01:06:24.500
make males more sexually active
is basically nonexistent.

01:06:24.500 --> 01:06:27.250
So critical, critical
proviso here.

01:06:27.250 --> 01:06:31.430
This is sex increasing
testosterone secretion, not

01:06:31.430 --> 01:06:33.440
the other way around.

01:06:33.440 --> 01:06:34.610
What else?

01:06:34.610 --> 01:06:37.590
Meanwhile, back to the
posterior pituitary.

01:06:37.590 --> 01:06:39.080
Was that a question?

01:06:39.080 --> 01:06:39.580
No.

01:06:39.580 --> 01:06:39.920
OK.

01:06:39.920 --> 01:06:41.030
That was a head scratch.

01:06:41.030 --> 01:06:41.590
OK.

01:06:41.590 --> 01:06:43.360
Back to the posterior pituitary.

01:06:43.360 --> 01:06:46.870
The other hormone coming
out from there, vasopressin.

01:06:46.870 --> 01:06:51.420
And oxytocin is to females
as vasopressin is to males.

01:06:51.420 --> 01:06:52.830
And we've already
heard something

01:06:52.830 --> 01:06:55.440
about this back in
the molecular genetics

01:06:55.440 --> 01:06:59.310
stuff in those if-then clauses
and unlikely ways in which you

01:06:59.310 --> 01:07:00.570
get mutations.

01:07:00.570 --> 01:07:04.620
vasopressin, vasopressin
also is found

01:07:04.620 --> 01:07:09.260
in the nervous system, where it
serves as neuromodulatory role.

01:07:09.260 --> 01:07:14.130
And vasopressin is critical
for forming a pair bond.

01:07:14.130 --> 01:07:16.220
Back to that business
about when you

01:07:16.220 --> 01:07:20.190
look at monogamous versus
polygamist species,

01:07:20.190 --> 01:07:21.510
what's going on?

01:07:21.510 --> 01:07:23.910
What you have uniquely
in the monogamous

01:07:23.910 --> 01:07:27.830
species is expression of
the vasopressin receptor

01:07:27.830 --> 01:07:32.731
gene on neurons that
released dopamine.

01:07:32.731 --> 01:07:36.810
In other words, male
secrete vasopressin.

01:07:36.810 --> 01:07:41.320
And if you are of a species
where vasopressin now goes

01:07:41.320 --> 01:07:45.540
and stimulates dopamine
neurons, you decide you really,

01:07:45.540 --> 01:07:48.720
really, really liked having
sex with this other vole.

01:07:48.720 --> 01:07:50.720
And you come back for more.

01:07:50.720 --> 01:07:54.520
And that's the driving force on
the formation of the pair bond.

01:07:54.520 --> 01:07:57.480
Incredible studies
showing that if you

01:07:57.480 --> 01:08:00.630
take male voles from
the polygamist species

01:08:00.630 --> 01:08:03.070
and, due to gene
transfer techniques--

01:08:03.070 --> 01:08:04.720
I've mentioned the
study already--

01:08:04.720 --> 01:08:08.220
but you now stick
vasopressin receptors

01:08:08.220 --> 01:08:12.050
into those dopamine neurons,
those polygamist males

01:08:12.050 --> 01:08:14.520
now become pair bonding males.

01:08:14.520 --> 01:08:16.810
They now become monogamous.

01:08:16.810 --> 01:08:19.319
So really interesting.

01:08:19.319 --> 01:08:21.960
What you then see
in these studies is

01:08:21.960 --> 01:08:24.960
you look at these monogamous
species where the males have

01:08:24.960 --> 01:08:27.750
vasopressin receptors on
these dopamine neurons,

01:08:27.750 --> 01:08:29.899
and you look at
individual males,

01:08:29.899 --> 01:08:32.290
and the ones who
have more receptors

01:08:32.290 --> 01:08:35.920
there are forming
pair bonds faster.

01:08:35.920 --> 01:08:38.620
It takes fewer rounds
of mating with a female

01:08:38.620 --> 01:08:41.229
to form a pair bond.

01:08:41.229 --> 01:08:43.510
So what about primates?

01:08:43.510 --> 01:08:46.960
So you start off looking at two
different primate species, one

01:08:46.960 --> 01:08:50.939
pair bonding, marmoset monkeys,
New World marmoset monkeys,

01:08:50.939 --> 01:08:53.479
and then one classic
tournament species,

01:08:53.479 --> 01:08:57.250
polygamous primate
species, rhesus monkeys.

01:08:57.250 --> 01:09:00.729
And what you see is
you've got the variant,

01:09:00.729 --> 01:09:04.830
the monogamous vole,
vasopressin receptor gene

01:09:04.830 --> 01:09:07.600
variant in the pair
bonding monkey species,

01:09:07.600 --> 01:09:08.830
in the marmosets.

01:09:08.830 --> 01:09:10.850
And you get the
polygamous version

01:09:10.850 --> 01:09:16.670
of the gene in the
rhesus monkeys.

01:09:16.670 --> 01:09:18.689
So it maps on there as well.

01:09:18.689 --> 01:09:22.240
So the more of this receptor
in these dopamine pathways

01:09:22.240 --> 01:09:25.140
within monogamous
species, the more rapidly

01:09:25.140 --> 01:09:26.810
they form a pair bond.

01:09:26.810 --> 01:09:30.960
And what you see is differences
in the mere presence of them

01:09:30.960 --> 01:09:34.990
in comparing pair bonding
versus non-pair bonding rodents

01:09:34.990 --> 01:09:37.600
and monkeys.

01:09:37.600 --> 01:09:40.020
So how about humans?

01:09:40.020 --> 01:09:43.189
First thing that comes
up is, among the apes,

01:09:43.189 --> 01:09:47.620
you also find the two
variants, the monogamous vole

01:09:47.620 --> 01:09:50.590
variant of the
vasopressin receptor gene

01:09:50.590 --> 01:09:53.450
and the polygamous male variant.

01:09:53.450 --> 01:09:55.380
So what species
do you see it in?

01:09:55.380 --> 01:09:59.510
In chimpanzees, you see
the polygamous vole species

01:09:59.510 --> 01:10:01.380
version.

01:10:01.380 --> 01:10:03.000
That makes lots of sense.

01:10:03.000 --> 01:10:06.430
They are a major polygamist
species in their behavior.

01:10:06.430 --> 01:10:08.740
But then, this
beautiful dichotomy

01:10:08.740 --> 01:10:12.260
comes crashing down
when you see that you've

01:10:12.260 --> 01:10:17.480
got the monogamous gene
version in bonobos.

01:10:17.480 --> 01:10:19.610
And as we will hear
about in a while,

01:10:19.610 --> 01:10:25.520
bonobos are the most
hyperpolygamously, hyper

01:10:25.520 --> 01:10:30.000
varietyish sexually behaving
organisms on the entire planet.

01:10:30.000 --> 01:10:33.220
They are as far as you could
get from a monogamous species

01:10:33.220 --> 01:10:36.180
as you can ever ask for,
if you ask for such things.

01:10:36.180 --> 01:10:40.110
And you've got the wrong type
of vasopressin receptor gene.

01:10:40.110 --> 01:10:42.610
Whatever is going on,
it's more complicated

01:10:42.610 --> 01:10:45.340
than the have the
version that winds up

01:10:45.340 --> 01:10:47.260
on the dopamine
neurons and you are

01:10:47.260 --> 01:10:50.760
going to have 50th wedding
anniversaries if you are a vole

01:10:50.760 --> 01:10:52.320
or you are a marmoset.

01:10:52.320 --> 01:10:55.760
And it's got to be more
complicated than that.

01:10:55.760 --> 01:10:57.690
So how about humans?

01:10:57.690 --> 01:11:00.350
And what you see
is not explicitly

01:11:00.350 --> 01:11:03.600
as much genetic
variability as some people

01:11:03.600 --> 01:11:06.080
having the monogamous vole
version and some people

01:11:06.080 --> 01:11:07.120
have the polygamist.

01:11:07.120 --> 01:11:09.440
But nonetheless,
you get variation.

01:11:09.440 --> 01:11:13.250
The gene basically is
about halfway in between.

01:11:13.250 --> 01:11:13.790
Whoa.

01:11:13.790 --> 01:11:16.790
We keep having that
theme over and over,

01:11:16.790 --> 01:11:20.500
all these different ways
of looking at body size,

01:11:20.500 --> 01:11:23.350
and sexual dimorphism,
and imprinted genes,

01:11:23.350 --> 01:11:24.470
and all that stuff.

01:11:24.470 --> 01:11:27.280
And humans keep winding
up being about a halfway

01:11:27.280 --> 01:11:29.450
between a classic
monogamous pair

01:11:29.450 --> 01:11:32.790
bonder and a classic
polygamist tournament species.

01:11:32.790 --> 01:11:36.780
So the basic human version of
it is somewhere in between.

01:11:36.780 --> 01:11:38.600
But you get variations.

01:11:38.600 --> 01:11:41.760
You've got genetic variations
that either look a little bit

01:11:41.760 --> 01:11:45.710
more like the monogamous vole
version or the polygamous vole

01:11:45.710 --> 01:11:46.670
version.

01:11:46.670 --> 01:11:49.810
And what studies have now
shown-- two different studies

01:11:49.810 --> 01:11:54.010
independently showing this--
have the monogamous vole

01:11:54.010 --> 01:11:54.950
version.

01:11:54.950 --> 01:11:59.690
And with the small effect, you
are more likely to get married,

01:11:59.690 --> 01:12:01.870
you are more likely
to remain married,

01:12:01.870 --> 01:12:03.960
and both you and
your partner are

01:12:03.960 --> 01:12:08.600
more likely to rate the
marriage as stable and happy.

01:12:08.600 --> 01:12:10.980
That's kind of interesting.

01:12:10.980 --> 01:12:14.260
Finally, in terms of
the role of vasopressin,

01:12:14.260 --> 01:12:17.380
in terms of attachment
in males, all of that,

01:12:17.380 --> 01:12:20.170
and in terms of
social connectiveness,

01:12:20.170 --> 01:12:22.930
a large body of
studies now have shown

01:12:22.930 --> 01:12:26.220
mutations in the
vasopressin receptor gene.

01:12:26.220 --> 01:12:26.720
OK.

